  "text": "On the other hand, if sustainability is defined as the survival of society, then it is most often linked with liveability and the quality of life (Bugliarello, 2006: 24) . Privacy is highly affected in dense areas and we might argue that those positive aspects of the suburban way of life, which make it more liveable, are discarded as part of sustainable development agendas. Living in detached housing, having space, privacy and a rural sense of connection to land, together with separation of functions and having quiet neighbourhoods, are some of important elements which influence why people still chose to live in suburbs (Grant, 2002: 78) and define them as 'liveable'. In addition, increasing density and generating a more compact way of living, is often associated with neoliberal intentions of maximising profit and minimising the quality of living space [CITATION_1] . While it does create a more energy efficient way of living, it neglects some aspects of liveability; the sustainability agendas are currently focusing on generating more dense areas without looking at the quality of these spaces and how to transform suburbia to be more sustainable.",
